          "type": "output_text",
          "text": "Recent top English-language posts on X discuss key challenges and ideas around AI agent skills, tool calling, and related capabilities.[[1]](https://x.com/i/status/2017884412352794810)[[2]](https://x.com/i/status/2018860160945635619)[[3]](https://x.com/i/status/2018010720789844284)\n\nHaseeb from Dragonfly proposes decomposing agent ecosystems into three searchable components: **Agents** (with APIs for natural language or JSON access), **Skills** (modular tools or systems that agents can absorb/purchase), and **Objects** (raw files for purchase). He notes this could work better outside social networks, like specialized databases.[[1]](https://x.com/i/status/2017884412352794810)\n\nWill Chen outlines two principles behind successful agent primitives (e.g., tool-calling, MCP, skills, heartbeats, subagents): 1) letting models conditionally load context, and 2) providing exactly what's needed to follow prompts.[[2]](https://x.com/i/status/2018860160945635619)\n\nDavid Cramer highlights a core limitation: agents struggle to reliably *discover* tools/skills, making progressive loading (e.g., MCP gateways with meta-tools like search/inspect/call/list) less effective than pre-loading subagents with task-specific tools.[[3]](https://x.com/i/status/2018010720789844284)",
